relatedLenses: [
	{lensId: "lens-documentation-as-product", relation: "complementsWith", context: "DP defines SSOT and glossary as documentation infrastructure. DL provides the terminological content: glossary entries with definitions, mappings, audience variants, juridical risk levels. DP is the documentation framework; DL is the vocabulary content that lives in it."},
	{lensId: "lens-trust-and-credibility-design", relation: "complementsWith", context: "TC builds trust through transparency and reliability. DL juridical implications ensures terms don't create unintended promises. 'Qualificado' with criteria + disclaimer: transparent about what it means and doesn't mean. TC is trust framework; DL is terminological trust — words that participants can rely on without being misled."},
	{lensId: "lens-stakeholder-communication", relation: "complementsWith", context: "SC defines audience-specific framing for communication. DL extends to terminology: same concept framed with different vocabulary per audience. SC says 'frame for audience'; DL says 'choose specific terms per audience — deságio for expert, taxa for professional, diferença for accessible.' SC is strategy; DL is vocabulary implementation."},
	{lensId: "lens-api-design-as-product", relation: "complementsWith", context: "API defines endpoint and field naming conventions. DL provides the correct English terms for domain concepts per glossary mapping. API says 'name endpoints clearly and consistently'; DL says 'use Supplier not Vendor, Anticipation not Transaction — per glossary.' API is naming convention; DL is naming content."},
	{lensId: "lens-multi-sided-platform-ux", relation: "complementsWith", context: "MUX defines per-side experience design. DL adds per-side terminology. Fornecedor sees accessible terms. FIDC sees expert terms. MUX designs the experience; DL designs the language within that experience."},
	{lensId: "lens-platform-evolution-and-backwards-compatibility", relation: "feedsInto", context: "PE defines how to evolve without breaking consumers. DL: term changes in API/events are breaking changes — PE's deprecation ceremony applies. Rename 'verified' to 'qualified' in API field: PE process (12-month notice, migration guide, version transition). Same rigor for terminology evolution as for API evolution."},
	{lensId: "lens-internationalization-and-localization-architecture", relation: "complementsWith", context: "IL defines multi-language architecture. DL provides the bilingual mapping content (pt-BR ↔ en) for all domain terms. When adding es-LATAM: DL mapping includes Spanish column for each term. IL is the i18n architecture; DL is the vocabulary content per language."},
]

limitations: [
	{description: "Glossary governance adds process overhead — every new term requires 7-criteria evaluation, review, documentation.", alternative: "Scale governance to risk. Internal-only code naming: lightweight (agent proposes in PR, founder approves in review, 5 minutes). Terms in contracts or public API: full ceremony with legal review. Most terms are low-risk internal: lightweight process. Few are high-risk external: full ceremony.", rationale: "Internal code naming: lightweight review. Contract-facing term: full governance. 90% of terms need 5 minutes; 10% need 1 hour."},
	{description: "Proprietary vocabulary ('Score de Cadeia') may not be adopted by market if Mesh doesn't reach sufficient scale.", alternative: "Use proprietary terms consistently regardless of current scale. Cost: zero extra beyond internal consistency (which is valuable independently). Upside: if Mesh succeeds, terms are established. Downside: if Mesh fails, terms were at least internally consistent. Asymmetric bet: upside is large, downside is zero.", rationale: "Zero extra cost beyond consistency. Upside: market adoption. Downside: none."},
	{description: "Bilingual mapping (pt-BR business / en code) creates translation burden and potential for mismatch.", alternative: "Glossary as single source with both columns reviewed together. Preserve untranslatable terms (Desagio, FIDC) rather than forcing inaccurate translation. Consistency > linguistic purity. When mapping is uncertain: preserve original with documentation.", rationale: "Some terms don't translate precisely. Preserving with documentation is more honest and less error-prone than forcing approximate translation."},
	{description: "Legal review of terms adds time and cost to terminology decisions.", alternative: "Legal review only for terms that appear externally: contracts, terms of use, API documentation, official communications, marketing materials. Internal-only terms (code variable names, internal docs): no legal review needed. Priority ranking: contracts > API > UI > marketing > code. Most new terms: internal. Few: external.", rationale: "Legal review by external exposure risk. Contract terms: always. Code variable names: never."},
	{description: "Maintaining 3 audience layers (expert/professional/accessible) for terminology adds content management overhead.", alternative: "3 layers only where expert term is genuinely unfamiliar to accessible audience. Many domain terms are universally understood: 'operação' (everyone knows), 'fornecedor' (everyone knows), 'status' (everyone knows). Only terms like 'deságio', 'coobrigação', 'HHI' need 3 layers. Selective, not universal: ~20% of terms need audience variants; 80% are universal.", rationale: "Selective calibration > universal 3-layer overhead. Most terms work for all audiences. Few need adaptation."},
]

rationale: "A Bloomberg criou vocabulário que se tornou o vocabulário do mercado financeiro. Na Mesh, cada termo que aparece em API, evento, interface, contrato e documentação se torna o vocabulário da construção civil se a plataforma vencer. Esta lens operacionaliza: linguagem ubíqua com glossário canônico e cross-context consistency (Evans 2003, vocabulary as competitive moat 2024+), critérios de seleção de termos com 7 dimensões incluindo precisão jurídica e diferenciação competitiva (term selection framework 2024+), consistência cross-layer com mapping table que garante 1 termo per conceito per layer (terminology mapping 2024+, code-language alignment DDD 2023+), implicações jurídicas de terminologia com legal review e disclaimers padronizados (terminological liability 2024+, legal term review 2024+), vocabulário como marca com 4-6 termos proprietários (category creation through vocabulary 2024+, vocabulary moat 2024+), calibração de linguagem por audiência com 3 layers de acessibilidade (terminology accessibility layers 2024+, term-explanation pairing 2024+), governança de terminologia com lifecycle formal de termos (terminology lifecycle 2024+), e mapeamento bilíngue pt-BR/en com preservação de termos intraduzíveis (bilingual mapping 2024+). Vocabulário é propriedade intelectual semântica — se a Mesh definir 'Score de Cadeia', 'Recebível Elegível', 'Qualificação de Fornecedor' como termos do mercado: concorrentes operam no território linguístico da Mesh."

}
